\tzpsection{Derivation Layer}
\paragraph{Primary Statement.}
The local topological dimension at the TZP may transition among nearby dimensional states:

\begin{equation}
\dim_p(M)\in\{n,n-1,n+1\}.
\end{equation}

\paragraph{Primary Derivation.}
Let $M$ be an $n$-dimensional manifold away from $p$. For $x\neq p$,

\begin{equation}
\dim_x(M)=n .
\end{equation}

At $p$, however, the metric degeneracy and lemniscatic self-intersection create a local ambiguity: two branches of the manifold meet at one point.

A self-intersection may locally reduce distinguishable dimensional freedom, while bifurcation into two branches may locally increase effective adjacency. Therefore the local dimensional value is not fixed to $n$ alone, but may occupy the set:

\begin{equation}
\dim_p(M)\in\{n-1,n,n+1\}.
\end{equation}

\paragraph{Interpretation.}
The TZP acts as a dimensional seam. It is not merely located inside a dimension; it controls the transition between neighboring effective dimensional states.
